      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Links Page, Curated Resources</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>resource page</strong> is a webpage that organises useful links, tools, articles, or references around a specific topic — created by universities, industry associations, blogs, or businesses to help their audience find trusted information centrally. In SEO, resource pages are high-value link building targets because their owners are motivated to add genuinely useful content and typically link with editorial intent.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Links page, curated resources</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Link Building</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Link type</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Editorial DoFollow</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Universities maintain career resource pages for students. Marketing blogs maintain tool collections for practitioners. Nonprofits maintain service lists for communities in need. Each of these pages represents a link-building opportunity — and unlike cold outreach asking for a favour, you are offering something the page owner actually wants: a better resource for their audience.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a resource page?</h2>
        <p>A resource page is any page whose primary purpose is to curate and link to useful external content on a defined topic. They are not articles or opinion pieces — they are organised collections of links, often with brief descriptions of each linked resource.</p>
        <p>Resource pages appear across almost every industry and topic:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>University departments</strong> — "Resources for marketing students" listing textbooks, journals, and tools</li>
          <li><strong>Industry associations</strong> — "Small business resources" with links to guides, templates, and service providers</li>
          <li><strong>Blogs and publications</strong> — "Best SEO tools" or "Recommended reading" pages curated by editors</li>
          <li><strong>Nonprofit organisations</strong> — mental health resources, legal aid directories, community service listings</li>
          <li><strong>Conference and event websites</strong> — speaker resource lists, reading lists, post-event resource roundups</li>
          <li><strong>Local chambers of commerce</strong> — business directories and community resource pages</li>
        </ul>
        <p>What makes these valuable for link building is the context: the page owner built the page specifically to help an audience find useful things. They are not opposed to adding more links — they are looking for reasons to add them.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why resource page links are different from regular outreach</div>
          <p>Most link building asks a publisher to do something extra (write about you, mention you in a future piece). Resource page outreach asks them to do something they already planned: keep their page useful. The alignment between your goal and their goal makes resource page outreach the most naturally accepted link building tactic.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why resource pages matter for link building</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Editorial intent = genuine authority signal.</strong> Links from well-maintained resource pages are editorially given — the page owner chose to add your link because it serves their audience. Google treats these as high-quality endorsements.</li>
          <li><strong>Targeted referral traffic.</strong> Resource pages attract visitors actively looking for solutions. A link from a marketing tools resource page drives qualified traffic — people already researching your category, not random visitors.</li>
          <li><strong>Curated pages pass authority.</strong> Resource pages on high-authority domains (universities, established publications) pass significant PageRank. A link from a university's "digital marketing resources" page carries more authority than most blog outreach targets.</li>
          <li><strong>Content discovery signal.</strong> Search engines crawl resource pages to discover new authoritative content. Being listed on curated pages in your niche accelerates indexation and establishes topical authority.</li>
          <li><strong>Sustainable link acquisition.</strong> Unlike trending content that earns links for a few weeks, resource page links are stable. Well-maintained resource pages keep their links for years, providing long-term authority.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How resource page link building works — 4 steps</h2>

        <h3>Step 1 — Find relevant resource pages</h3>
        <p>Use Google search operators to surface resource pages in your niche:</p>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Search operators for finding resource pages</span><br>
          "resources" + <span class="uf-new">your topic</span><br>
          "useful links" + <span class="uf-new">your topic</span><br>
          inurl:resources + <span class="uf-new">your topic</span><br>
          "best resources for" + <span class="uf-new">your topic</span><br>
          intitle:resources + <span class="uf-new">your topic</span>
        </div>
        <p>Ahrefs Content Explorer can also find pages with "resources" in their title that already link to competitors — giving you a pre-qualified list of pages where your content would fit alongside existing links.</p>

        <h3>Step 2 — Evaluate page quality</h3>
        <p>Not every resource page is worth targeting. Check for:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Active maintenance — last updated within the past year</li>
          <li>Reasonable link count — 10-100 links (not thousands)</li>
          <li>Topical relevance to your content</li>
          <li>Domain authority above 30 (DA/DR metric from Ahrefs or Moz)</li>
          <li>Real organic traffic — check Ahrefs Site Explorer or Semrush</li>
          <li>Editorial standards — does the curator clearly select links, not accept any submission?</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Step 3 — Create link-worthy content</h3>
        <p>Resource page curators only add links that genuinely serve their audience. Content that earns placement:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Original research</strong> — surveys, data studies, industry benchmarks</li>
          <li><strong>Comprehensive guides</strong> — definitive topic coverage that saves readers from finding multiple sources</li>
          <li><strong>Free tools and calculators</strong> — utilities that solve a specific problem</li>
          <li><strong>Templates and frameworks</strong> — reusable assets practitioners actually use</li>
          <li><strong>Infographics with original data</strong> — visual formats curators love for their audience engagement</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Step 4 — Send personalised outreach</h3>
        <p>Keep it short. Reference the specific resource page. Explain in one sentence why your content adds value to their audience that isn't already covered. Do not attach anything — link to your page. Follow up once after 7-10 days if no response.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Resource page vs link farm — the critical difference</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Quality Resource Page</th><th>Link Farm</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Editorial review</strong></td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Yes — curator selects links</td>
                <td class="cell-no">No — accepts any submission</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Topical relevance</strong></td>
                <td class="cell-yes">High — curated around specific topic</td>
                <td class="cell-no">Low or none — mixed categories</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Link descriptions</strong></td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Descriptive, adds context</td>
                <td class="cell-no">Bare URLs or keyword-stuffed anchor text</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>User value</strong></td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Clear — helps audience find trusted resources</td>
                <td class="cell-no">None — exists solely for link exchange</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>SEO risk</strong></td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Low — natural editorial link</td>
                <td class="cell-no">High — Google penalises link schemes</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — targeting any page with "resources" in the URL</div>
          <p>Many link builders target every page with "/resources/" in the URL, including paid directories, link exchanges, and low-quality aggregators. Check that the page has real editorial standards before outreaching. A link from a manipulative linking page can harm your profile; a no-link from a quality page is better than a yes from a spammy one.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Resource page link building vs broken link building</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Resource page outreach</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Pitch to pages actively curating links</li>
              <li>No broken link required — offer new value</li>
              <li>Works for new content</li>
              <li>Higher response rate due to clear mutual benefit</li>
              <li>Best for comprehensive guides and tools</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Broken link building</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Find dead links on resource pages</li>
              <li>Offer your page as a replacement</li>
              <li>Requires finding 404s at scale</li>
              <li>Stronger pitch — you're solving a problem they have</li>
              <li>Best for content replacing existing resources</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for resource page link building</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Target actively maintained pages.</strong> Check when the page was last updated. A resource page not updated in 3 years is unlikely to add new links regardless of how good your pitch is.</li>
          <li><strong>Suggest only content that fits the page's existing theme.</strong> If the page covers "digital marketing tools" and you're pitching a comprehensive guide to email marketing, you need a specific email tool resource — not a generic guide.</li>
          <li><strong>Write personalised emails, not templates.</strong> Reference something specific on their page. Name the section where your link would fit. Generic outreach emails get ignored; specific, helpful emails get responses.</li>
          <li><strong>Follow up once, politely.</strong> A single follow-up after 7-10 days is professional. Multiple follow-ups are annoying. If they don't respond to two emails, move on.</li>
          <li><strong>Build relationships with resource page curators.</strong> A curator who added your first link is more likely to add future links. Promote their page. Engage with their content. Long-term relationships beat one-off transactions.</li>
          <li><strong>Track placements and maintain your content.</strong> Update linked content when it becomes outdated. Broken or stale content gets removed from resource pages. Keep your linked assets current to retain placements long-term.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common resource page mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Pitching irrelevant content.</strong> A WordPress plugin review does not belong on a "local government digital services" resource page. Relevance is the first filter every curator applies.</li>
          <li><strong>Mass email outreach with no personalisation.</strong> Curators receive dozens of pitches per week. An obviously templated email goes straight to the trash. Personalised emails that reference the specific page convert at 5-10x the rate.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring page quality.</strong> Not all links help. A link from a page with 500 outbound links to unrelated domains passes negligible authority and may associate your site with low-quality link profiles.</li>
          <li><strong>Targeting paid directories pretending to be resource pages.</strong> Some pages that look like resource pages charge for inclusion. Paid links violate Google's guidelines — always check whether the page accepts payment.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
